Tutorial 3 - ThreeJS Portfolio Website

9 steps

We have learnt how to create and add 3D Mesh objects to our website. We have also learnt how to animate and manipulate our camera objects as well.

Here, we want to put everything we have learnt into good use! We will create a portfolio website and include some form of ThreeJS technology. Each time the user scrolls in the website, we will do a zooming-out feature which shows our ThreeJS components in the background.

So what are you waiting for? Quickly open your code editor as we build our very own personal portfolio website with ThreeJS!

For technical help, be sure to join our StackUp Discord and head to the 🆘｜general-help channel.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

ThreeJS Coordinates and Camera Movement
Deploying a site via Firebase, Vercel or Netlify using command line interface

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to

  • Animate Meshes in ThreeJS
  • Animate the Camera object when the user scrolls
  • Fill 3D Scene with the Stars as the fillers in the backgrounds

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 9

  • Step 1: Setting Up Our Workspace

    Let’s open our coding editor. Your workspace should open the root folder that we created previously, i.e. StackUp-ThreeJS. Once you have done so, open your terminal in your code editor and ensure that the current working directory is the root folder.

    To get started with Vite, in our terminal, enter the following command you see below.

    npm create vite

    Initialise with Vite

    The command above will initialise the project with Vite. Once you have done that, you will be prompted to enter the name of the project.

    Enter threejs-portfolio-website in your terminal.

    Selection of Framework

    Once that is done, you will be asked to select the framework of the project you would like to use. In this case, select Vanilla, and hit the Enter key. The item that is currently selected will be underlined.

    Choosing a Programming Language

    Next, when prompted to select a variant, choose JavaScript. Once done, you should see a message that says Done. Now run the following commands in your terminal.

    cd threejs-portfolio-website
npm install three
npm run dev

    In the three commands, the first line will change the current working directory to the project directory we have initialised with Vite. The second line will install the dependencies we need, in this project, we will need to have threejs installed. You might be wondering why it is “install three” instead of “install threejs”. This is because the package on NPM is called “three”. Lastly, the last command is to set up and run our local development server as we develop our web application. This local development server has a great benefit which grants us “hot-reloading”, which is the ability to see our code changes live.

  • Step 2: Index.html

    Now we will work on the structure of the website. Open index.html and replace the existing code with the code found here.

    This is all the code we need to create for this file. The elements and structures are the same as our previous campaigns.

    Important!: As part of the requirement of this quest, you are to add your StackUp username to the <title> in line 6 and also to line 77.

    From line 81 to line 165, you will realise that the code looks quite repetitive. This sample generated text will serve as a placeholder.

    We will write internal CSS from line 7 to line 67. This will help us to style our elements. In line 35, we will style our container there to have an absolute positioning so that we can fix our container to the left side of the website, while we reserve the right side of our website to view the ThreeJS component.

    Since ThreeJS will be taking up the full width and height of the website, in line 52, we will also set the opacity of the background to have a translucent feel so that the ThreeJS component can be shown behind the website content.

    Lastly, you may wonder what is the “dvh” in lines 22 and 23. This is a special CSS unit that takes in the viewport space instead of the actual display space. For example, typically, we will use Vertical Height or Vertical Width, but using those will take the Height and Width of the display. But using “dvh” or “dvw” takes into account the other components of the web browser like the search field, tabs etc. If you would like to learn more, feel free to visit this article to find out more.

  • Step 3: Image Sourcing

    Now, we will be sourcing the image that we need --  a personal portrait or avatar. In the previous step, we added the stylings in line 26 to line 32 to style our image. Once you have the image, add it to the public folder of this project. Please rename your image to profile.jpg.

    Important!: If your image extension is not in JPG, you must change the image source in line 76 of index.html file.

  • Step 4: Creating our Scene with ThreeJS

    Now we are ready to create our scene in ThreeJS. Open main.js and replace the existing code with the code below.

    import * as THREE from 'three';

// Creating the scene
const scene = new THREE.Scene();

// Creating the camera
const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
camera.position.z = 0.23;
camera.position.x = 0.0046;
camera.position.y = 0.0046;

// Creating the renderer
const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true });
renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
document.getElementById('app').appendChild(renderer.domElement);

// Set the background colour of the scene
renderer.setClearColor('#1d1135');
    JavaScript

    We will import the module “three” into our project. Using import * as THREE means that we import all the files from “three” under the variable “THREE”. Next in line 4, we create a new scene instance and will now be able to add a new Perspective Camera, that takes on the full width and height of the website, into the scene as well.

    Then, in line 15, we append the renderer of ThreeJS to the empty <div> we have created in the previous step. We will query the element by the id of “app”.

    In line 18, we set the background colour as purple.

  • Step 5: Adding Meshes to Our Scene

    We will now be adding a cube, a torus (a donut shape) and 100 stars to our scene. We will also be adding some lights as well. Within the same file, main.js, add the code below to the end of the file. 

    // Creating a geometry (a cube in this case)
const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1, 1, 1);
const material = new THREE.MeshPhongMaterial({ color: 0x00ff00 });
const cube = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);
scene.add(cube);

// Adding a torus below the cube
const geometryTorus = new THREE.TorusGeometry(10, 3, 16, 100);
const materialTorus = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0xff6347 });
const torus = new THREE.Mesh(geometryTorus, materialTorus);
scene.add(torus);

const stars = new THREE.Group();
// Adding stars to the scene
const addStar = () => {
    const geometry = new THREE.SphereGeometry(0.25);
    const material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0xffffff });
    const star = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);

    // Randomly position the star
    const [x, y, z] = Array(3).fill().map(() => THREE.MathUtils.randFloatSpread(100));
    star.position.set(x, y, z);
    scene.add(star);
    stars.add(star);
}

// Adding 1000 stars to the scene
Array(1000).fill().forEach(addStar);
scene.add(stars);

// Creating a point light
const pointLight = new THREE.PointLight(0xffffff);
pointLight.position.set(5, 5, 5);
scene.add(pointLight);

// Creating an ambient light
const ambientLight = new THREE.AmbientLight(0x404040);
scene.add(ambientLight);
    JavaScript

    From line 21 to 24 we create and add a cube to our scene, and from line 26 to 30, we add a torus to our scene. There is not much difference when adding a cube or a torus. The only difference is in line 21 and line 27 where we set the geometry to differing 3D Shapes. A rule of thumb when adding shapes is setting the geometry and the material of the shape. Once you have done both, you will be ready to create the mesh for your objects as shown on lines 23 and 29.

    Next in line 32 to line 47, we create multiple stars in the background to fill up the blank spaces in the background. We first create a group in line 32. Next, we create a function (line 34 to 44) to create the stars based on the same steps we used for the cube and torus. Since we want to add multiple stars, we need to render each star to a random location throughout our 3D Space. As such, using line 40, we will grab a random location and set the stars to position at those random locations. Lastly, in line 47, we will call the addStar() function in line 34, 1,000 times and the function will run 1,000 times to spawn 100 stars at 1,000 random locations.

    Finally, in lines 51 to 57, we add a point light and an ambient light to illuminate the virtual environment.

    At this point, your main.js should have 57 lines of code. You may refer to the image below.

  • Step 6: Scroll Handling and Animation

    We will now work on animating our camera and cube to respond to the whenever our users scroll the website. We will use the same file, main.js, to continue writing our code. Add the code snippet below, and your file should have 94 lines of code.

    // Scroll Event
document.body.onscroll = scrollHandler;

// Move the camera based on the scroll position
function scrollHandler() {
    // Move the camera based on the scroll position
    const t = document.body.getBoundingClientRect().top;
    cube.rotation.x += 0.05;
    cube.rotation.y += 0.075;
    cube.rotation.z += 0.05;

    // Move the camera based on the scroll position
    camera.position.z = t * -0.01;
    camera.position.x = t * -0.0002;
    camera.position.y = t * -0.0002;
}

// Animation function
function animate() {
    requestAnimationFrame(animate);

    // Rotate the cube
    cube.rotation.x += 0.01;
    cube.rotation.y += 0.01;

    // Rotate the torus
    torus.rotation.x += 0.005;
    torus.rotation.y += 0.0075;


    // Render the scene with the camera
    renderer.render(scene, camera);
}

// Start the animation
animate();
    JavaScript

    Whenever our user scrolls, it will trigger the scrollHandler() function that we have created in line 60. We want to move our cube as we scroll as well. In line 65, we will obtain the value of the top bounding client value, using the .getBoundingClientRect(), to be the constant such that when the user scrolls back to the same position, it will zoom back to the initial position. A bounding client rect values of the element’s top, bottom, right and left, relative to the parent container. Using this function, .getBoundingClientRect(), we can obtain the top value of our container in relation to the application window size.

    Once we have obtained the constant t, we will use it to multiply the value as shown in lines 71 to 73 to achieve the effect of zooming back to the same initial position. Without this constant, it will not achieve a linear rubber banding effect.

    Since we want to animate our objects when no scroll is detected, we will also animate our cube and torus in the background (lines 81 to line 86).

    And that is it! We are done with all the code we need. Next, we will build our application to host it on our static web hosting server.

  • Step 7: Building Our Application

    And that is it! Congratulations on making it to this point. Once we are satisfied with our project, it is time to build it for the web. What Vite will do is they will compile the code base across multiple files into one HTML file. Open a new terminal and ensure your current working directory is threejs-portfolio-website. Once you have done so, run the following command.

    npm run build

    This code will simply create a build of the application and place the build into a new folder called dist. Whatever is within this folder is the final product that can be used in production. 

  • Step 8: Project Initialisation and Code Deployment (With Netlify)

    You can host your static site on Firebase, Vercel (instructions are in our Discord server) or Netlify. This tutorial provides instructions for Netlify only. You can choose one of the three web hosts. Do note that the deployment is done via command line interface.

    Firstly, we will need to install the Netlify CLI tool using the following command in your terminal:

    npm install netlify-cli -g

    You will also need to create an account on Netlify. Thereafter, ensure that you are logged in to Netlify on your browser.

    Next, we will obtain an access token so that you can deploy your project from your terminal. We will use the following command in your terminal:

    netlify login

    A new browser tab or window will be opened asking you to authorize Netlify CLI to access Netlify on your behalf. Click on the Authorize button. In the event that the browser tab or window is not opened, you can also copy the URL in your terminal and input it in your browser. Once authorization has been granted, your terminal should now have the message "You are now logged into your Netlify account!"

    Next, in your terminal, enter 

    netlify deploy

    You will come across the following prompts and these are the responses you should make:

    What would you like to do?: Create & configure a new site

    Team: <choose the default option>

    Site name: <yourusername>-threejs-website (ensure you replace <yourusername> with your StackUp username)

    When asked to provide a publish directory, enter dist. Once the files have been uploaded, you will be provided with a "Website Draft URL". Go to that website and check that your website works as intended. Scroll down and see the changes. 

    If everything looks good, use the following command:

    netlify deploy --prod

    Once again, you will be asked for the publish directory. Use dist.

    When you see the message "Deploy is live!" and your website URL is provided, you know that your site has been successfully deployed. Visit your website again and ensure that everything works well.

  • Step 9: Stacking It Up!

    You have reached the end!

    Web Link
